    "text": "The Rydberg spectroscopy readout supplies only the Rydberg frequency and the fine-structure constant, both of which are measurable in terrestrial laboratories without any cosmological input.",
    "topic": "Rydberg data independence"
  },
  {
    "text": "The electron boundary action in MAT is computed entirely from the Rydberg frequency and the fine-structure constant, with no functional dependence on the Newton constant or the Hubble parameter.",
    "topic": "Electron boundary action derivation"
  },
  {
    "text": "The Planck-unit system reconstruction maps the electron boundary action to gravitational scale, causing the Newton constant G to appear as a derived quantity, not as an empirical input or calibration.",
    "topic": "Emergence of G"
  },
  {
    "text": "The procedure does not require a Hubble calibration because it never invokes the Hubble constant; the scale setting arises from the Rydberg constant, which is an atomic and not a cosmological constant.",
    "topic": "Absence of Hubble calibration"
  }
]
